Melatonin as a well-known hormone produced by pineal gland has diverse physiological functions including affecting circadian rhythms [19], changing cellular redox status [20], and anti-tumor [21]. Notably, it has been reported that melatonin exerts its multiple bioactivities, especially its anti-tumor effect, partially via STAT3 pathway [22–25]. Another “old friend” salicylic acid, which is famous for its derivative acetylsalicylic acid, a classical anti-inflammation agent also known as Aspirin, once again amazed us with its novel derivatives represented by S3I-201.1066 entitled with great anti-cancer activity by inhibiting STAT3 aberrant activation and functions in human cancer cells [26–28]. In our previous research, the designed compounds following the combination strategy between melatonin and N-salicyloyl derivatives had been proven possessing satisfying anti-neuroinflammatory activity by inhibiting cyclooxygenase (COX), scavenging radicals, and inhibiting activation of glial cells [29] (Fig. 2
                     ). The modification also granted a lower acidity to these compounds compared to the majority of non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) by shielding the acid groups. In consideration of a “reversed” pH gradient (intracellular pH is higher than the extracellular pH) in most cancer cells compared to normal cells [30], and most anticancer drugs are ionizable, an appropriate pKa trait of anti-cancer drugs, which determines the portion of drugs in a neutral form (accessible to cancer focus and permeable into cancer cytomembrane), could enhance the drugs’ efficiency [31]. Enlightened by the studies above, a series of modifications had been done on the structure of melatonin and N-salicylic acid following the similar modification strategy with the aim of making a combination of anti-cancer and anti-inflammation properties from the two fragments (Scheme 1
                     ).
